My name is Cathy Williamson and I am a 9 1/2-year, Triple Negative Breast Cancer survivor, and proud ambassador for the @tnbcfoundation Power of 3, TNBC Day Campaign. 

Today is March 3rd, which is Triple Negative Breast Cancer Awareness Day, kicking off an entire month I’d education, awareness, and fundraising. Check out link in my bio to learn more. 

3 things I wish I had known when I was diagnosed…

1. TNBC is known as the “scary” breast cancer and the one with the worst outcome. I found out that you can beat this kind of cancer and wish I had not listened to what everyone and the media said about it. 

2. You have to be your own advocate for any kind of medical issue. Whatever you are diagnosed with, find THE BEST doctor that you can in that field. 

3. The last thing that I wish I had known going into this, is that it would actually turn out to be a gift that I wouldn’t trade for anything. 

I am here for anyone going through breast cancer and consider it a privilege to help! 

#TNBCDAY #TNBCDAY2023 #tnbcfoundation #powerof3

Kathy leads a busy life. She is a former OR/ER nurse training for an Ironman competition. She and her husband have also biked the United States together. She received the Cochlear™ Kanso(R) 2 Sound Processor and a cochlear implant almost a year ago, and she said it has been the greatest gift! She can now hear her husband talk as they ride bikes together, whereas before, she had to read his lips. She can be active with her sound processor, hear her coaches and participate more fully in the life around her.

Cochlear implants are seriously changing people’s lives. You don’t think about what you would miss out on when you have your hearing. I was struck by Kathy’s excitement and joy of being able to hear when she is now at dinners with her friends or training for her upcoming competition. Grab your girls (yes, those girls!) and get screened for breast cancer! We talk about this so much during the month of October, but it should be part of our general self-care. #ad I am so thankful for mammograms because that is the way I found my cancer. I was diagnosed 10 years ago with Triple Negative Breast Cancer, and thank God that the radiologist saw a calcification that looked strange to him. My tumor was actually hiding in the duct, and the calcification was why he had me get a biopsy. My life changed in a big way as I had a double mastectomy followed by chemo, radiation, and reconstruction. I don’t really recommend it (get a mammogram)!

Regular screening can catch cancer early when it is easier to treat. I think all women should start having them at 40 years old. This year, 300,500 will be diagnosed with breast cancer, and 3,000 will be men. Because of mammograms and better treatment, death rates from breast cancer have gone down 43% since 1989! 

The @americancancersociety is currently investing more than 75 MILLION in breast cancer-specific research through 160 grants. I am so grateful to organizations like the American Cancer Society for helping women and men overcome this potentially deadly disease. Now, go grab your girls and make the appointment! 

Talk to a doctor and visit cancer.org/getscreened to learn more.
